node.text:
From a perfect trip into the backcountry earlier this summer 🏕 

I’m looking forward to the rain and some cooler temps this week & hoping they provide some much needed relief for the many wildfires currently burning throughout BC and beyond.

Thanks for the photo @mddyelrck

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CAROLINE | Adventure + Travel in Canadian Rockies. May be an image of nature.
Photo by CAROLINE | Adventure + Travel in Canadian Rockies with @goldiekatie_. May be an image of nature and lake.

node.text:
It’s hard not to crave a lake day when the water looks like this 😍

This summer I’ve definitely embraced a slower pace, taking more time for things like self-care and my fave hobbies. Last year in comparison was non-stop road trips and backcountry camping with hikes in between and often little sleep. Don’t get me wrong, it was a great summer but by mid October I was definitely feeling a bit burned out and craved some much needed downtime at home. It’s a balance I’m still constantly trying to find but it’s definitely been a bit easier this summer with staying close to home.

node.text:
Here’s a throwback to my third ever backcountry trip in bear country.

My first two short overnight trips had been uneventful. Although despite that I was still a bit nervous about spending two nights deep in grizzly country with only the thin walls of my tent between me and any overnight visitors.

Our first night went smoothly enough but on our approach to our second campsite of the trip we were informed a momma griz and her two cubs had been seen walking through and hanging about camp that very morning. When we arrived we debated our campsite for about an hour between an isolated site near the stream, a site surrounded by huckleberries or a site that was close by another but on a path that seemed like the obvious way to walk into camp. We finally settled on the latter site taking comfort in having other campers nearby.

As the sun begun to sink below the mountains all was calm around camp. Our nerves had settled, our bags had been double and triple checked for anything with even the slightest hint of a scent and all food/toiletries hung safely in the designated spot. At approximately 5 am the unthinkable happened, we both awoke suddenly to the unmistakable sound of a bear bellowing directly outside our tent, probably only a few feet away. This was followed by grunting and huffing and the sounds of paws thumping as the bears moved around our tent and onto the one next to us where they stayed for what seemed like at least an hour. They had no reason to claw their way into our tent but that didn’t stop our thoughts from going there.

About two hours later after I’d decided to pretend it wasn’t happening and force myself back to sleep, we cautiously emerged from our tent to see the large mother grizzly and her two decently sized cubs grazing close by on the hillside. Our neighbors had awoken to find their packs had been tossed about but somehow had slept through the entire thing.

It was a memorable trip to say the least and a good reminder that bear safety rules are there for a reason. Something had attracted those bears to our neighbors packs and caused them to toss them about while leaving ours completely undisturbed.

Thanks for the photo @montanalex

node.text:
I just got back from my first backcountry trip of the season and I can’t wait to share more from that, but in the meantime here’s a shot from a fun sunset adventure a few days back.

Between historic heatwaves, flooding, wildfires, high demand for permits and bridges washing out my initial backcountry plans didn’t quite pan out but I’m pretty sure plan C was meant to be as it was definitely a trip to remember! Stories coming soon…

Thanks for your help with this shot @samanthalreid
